<section xml:id="week10-activity">
  <title>Week 10 Activity</title>
  <subsection xml:id="activity-directional-derivatives">
    <title>Directional Derivatives</title>
    <activity>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Calculate the directional derivative of the function
          <me>
            f(x,y) = 3x + 5y - 2xy + x^2 - y^2 
          </me>
          at the point <m>p = (0,-2)</m> in the direction <m>v =
          (-1,-1)</m>. 
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          The method of calculating directional derivatives is to take
          the dot product of the <emph>unit</emph> direction vector
          with the gradient of the function. First I calculate the
          gradient.
          <md>
            <mrow>
              \nabla f(x,y) \amp = \left( 3 -2y +2x, 5 - 2x - 2y
              \right) 
            </mrow>
          </md>
          Then I calculate the unit vector for the given direction.
          <md>
            <mrow>
              |v| \amp = \sqrt{(-1)^2 + (-1)^2} = \sqrt{2} 
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \frac{1}{|v|}v \amp = \left( \frac{-1}{\sqrt{2}},
              \frac{-1}{\sqrt{2}} \right) 
            </mrow>
          </md>
          Then I take the dot product to produce the directional
          derivative.
          <md>
            <mrow>
              D_v f(x,y) \amp = \frac{1}{|v|} v \cdot \nabla f(x,y) =
              \frac{-3 + 2y - 2x}{\sqrt{2}} + \frac{-5 + 2x +
              2y}{\sqrt{2}} = \frac{-8 + 4y}{\sqrt{2}} 
            </mrow>
          </md>
          Finally, I evaluate at the given point.
          <md>
            <mrow>
              D_v f(0,-2) \amp = \frac{-8 - 8}{\sqrt{2}} =
              \frac{-16}{\sqrt{2}} 
            </mrow>
          </md>
          I could have first evaluated the gradient at the point and
          then taken the dot product with the unit direction; that
          order of calculations would have produced the same result.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </activity>
    <activity>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Calculate the directional derivative of the function
          <me>
            f(x,y) = \cos (x - y)
          </me>
          at the point <m>p = \left( \frac{\pi}{2}, \frac{\pi}{2}
          \right)</m> in the direction <m>v = (2,1)</m>. 
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          The method of calculating directional derivatives is to take
          the dot product of the <emph>unit</emph> direction vector
          with the gradient of the function. First I calculate the
          gradient.
          <md>
            <mrow>
              \nabla f(x,y) \amp = \left( -\sin (x-y), \sin (x-y)
              \right) 
            </mrow>
          </md>
          Then I calculate the unit vector for the given direction.
          <md>
            <mrow>
              |v| \amp = \sqrt{2^2 + 1^2} = \sqrt{5} 
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \frac{1}{|v|}v \amp = \left( \frac{2}{\sqrt{5}},
              \frac{1}{\sqrt{5}} \right) 
            </mrow>
          </md>
          Then I take the dot product to produce the directional
          derivative.
          <md>
            <mrow>
              D_v f(x,y) \amp = \frac{1}{|v|} v \cdot \nabla f(x,y) =
              \frac{-2\sin(x-y)}{\sqrt{5}} + \frac{\sin
              (x-y)}{\sqrt{2}} = \frac{-\sin (x-y)}{\sqrt{5}} 
            </mrow>
          </md>
          Finally, I evaluate at the given point.
          <md>
            <mrow>
              D_v f\left( \frac{\pi}{2}, \frac{\pi}{2} \right) \amp =
              \frac{-\sin \left( \frac{\pi}{2} - \frac{\pi}{2}
              \right)}{\sqrt{5}} = \frac{-\sin 0}{\sqrt{5}} = 0 
            </mrow>
          </md>
          I could have first evaluated the gradient at the point and
          then taken the dot product with the unit direction; that
          order of calculations would have produced the same result.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </activity>
    <activity>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Calculate the directional derivative of the function
          <me>
            f(x,y) = xy - yz + yz^2 - x^3
          </me>
          at the point <m>p = (3,1,-2)</m> in the direction <m>v =
          (1,3,1)</m>. 
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          The method of calculating directional derivatives is to take
          the dot product of the <emph>unit</emph> direction vector
          with the gradient of the function. First I calculate the
          gradient.
          <md>
            <mrow>
              \nabla f(x,y) \amp = \left( y - 3x^2, x - z + z^2, -y +
              2yz \right) 
            </mrow>
          </md>
          Then I calculate the unit vector for the given direction.
          <md>
            <mrow>
              |v| \amp = \sqrt{1^2 + 3^2 +1^2} = \sqrt{11} 
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \frac{1}{|v|}v \amp = \left( \frac{1}{\sqrt{11}},
              \frac{3}{\sqrt{11}} , \frac{1}{\sqrt{11}} \right) 
            </mrow>
          </md>
          Then I take the dot product to produce the directional
          derivative.
          <md>
            <mrow>
              D_v f(x,y) \amp = \frac{1}{|v|} v \cdot \nabla f(x,y) =
              \frac{y - 3x^2}{\sqrt{11}} + \frac{3x - 3z +
              3z^2}{\sqrt{11}} + \frac{-z + 2yz}{\sqrt{11}} 
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \amp = \frac{3x
              + y - 4z - 3x^2 + 3z^2 + 2yz}{\sqrt{11}} 
            </mrow>
          </md>
          Finally, I evaluate at the given point.
          <md>
            <mrow>
              D_v f(3,1,-2) \amp = \frac{9 + 1 + 8 - 27 + 12 -
              2}{\sqrt{11}} = \frac{1}{\sqrt{11}}
            </mrow>
          </md>
          I could have first evaluated the gradient at the point and
          then taken the dot product with the unit direction; that
          order of calculations would have produced the same result.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </activity>
    <activity>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Calculate the directional derivative of the function
          <me>
            f(x,y) = e^{xyz}
          </me>
          at the point <m>p = (0,0,3)</m> in the direction <m>v =
          (-1,0,-2)</m>. 
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          The method of calculating directional derivatives is to take
          the dot product of the <emph>unit</emph> direction vector
          with the gradient of the function. First I calculate the
          gradient.
          <md>
            <mrow>
              \nabla f(x,y) \amp = \left( yze^{xyz}, xze^{xyz},
              xye^{xyz} \right) 
            </mrow>
          </md>
          Then I calculate the unit vector for the given direction.
          <md>
            <mrow>
              |v| \amp = \sqrt{(-1)^2 + 0^2 + (-2)^2} = \sqrt{5}
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \frac{1}{|v|}v \amp = \left( \frac{-1}{\sqrt{5}}, 0,
              \frac{-2}{\sqrt{5}} \right) 
            </mrow>
          </md>
          Then I take the dot product to produce the directional
          derivative.
          <md>
            <mrow>
              D_v f(x,y) \amp = \frac{1}{|v|} v \cdot \nabla f(x,y) =
              \frac{-yze^{xyz}}{\sqrt{5}} +
              \frac{-2xye^{xyz}}{\sqrt{5}} =
              \frac{-(yz+2xy)e^{xyz}}{\sqrt{5}} 
            </mrow>
          </md>
          Finally, I evaluate at the given point.
          <md>
            <mrow>
              D_v f(0,0,3) \amp = \frac{-(0 + 0)e^0}{\sqrt{5}} = 0 
            </mrow>
          </md>
          I could have first evaluated the gradient at the point and
          then taken the dot product with the unit direction; that
          order of calculations would have produced the same result.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </activity>
    <activity>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Calculate the directional derivative of the function
          <me>
            f(x,y) = \frac{x^2 + y^2}{1 + z^2}
          </me>
          at the point <m>p = (2,0,-2)</m> in the direction <m>v =
          (1,1,1)</m>. 
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          The method of calculating directional derivatives is to take
          the dot product of the <emph>unit</emph> direction vector
          with the gradient of the function. First I calculate the
          gradient.
          <md>
            <mrow>
              \nabla f(x,y) \amp = \left( \frac{2x}{1+z^2},
              \frac{2y}{1+z^2}, \frac{-2x(x^2 + y^2)}{(1+z^2)^2}
              \right) 
            </mrow>
          </md>
          Then I calculate the unit vector for the given direction.
          <md>
            <mrow>
              |v| \amp = \sqrt{1^2 + 1^2 + 1^2} = \sqrt{3} 
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \frac{1}{|v|}v \amp = \left( \frac{1}{\sqrt{3}},
              \frac{1}{\sqrt{3}}, \frac{1}{\sqrt{3}} \right) 
            </mrow>
          </md>
          Then I take the dot product to produce the directional
          derivative.
          <md>
            <mrow>
              D_v f(x,y) \amp = \frac{1}{|v|} v \cdot \nabla f(x,y) =
              \frac{1}{\sqrt{3}} \left( \frac{2x}{1+z^2} +
              \frac{2y}{1+z^2} + \frac{-2z(x^2+y^2)}{(1+z^2)^2}
              \right) 
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \amp = \frac{ 2x(1+z^2) + 2y(1+z^2) - 2zx^2 -
              2zy^2}{\sqrt{3}(1+z^2)^2} 
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \amp = \frac{2x + 2y - 2x^2z - 2y^2 z + 2xz^2 +
              2yz^2}{\sqrt{3}(1+z^2)^2} 
            </mrow>
          </md>
          Finally, I evaluate at the given point.
          <md>
            <mrow>
              D_v f(2,0,-2) \amp =\frac{2(2) + 2(0) - 2(2)^2(-2) -
              2(0)^2(2) + 2(2)(-2)^2 +
              2(0)(-2)^2}{\sqrt{3}(1+(-2)^2)^2} 
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \amp = \frac{4 + 0 + 16 - 0 + 16 + 0}{\sqrt{(5)^2}} =
              \frac{36}{25\sqrt{3}}
            </mrow>
          </md>
          I could have first evaluated the gradient at the point and
          then taken the dot product with the unit direction; that
          order of calculations would have produced the same result.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </activity>
